<h1><span style="color: rgb(230, 126, 35);">Runestone interactive - author
        toolkit </span></h1>
<h3><span
        style="font-family: 'book antiqua', palatino, serif; font-size: 14pt; color: rgb(132, 63, 161);">Describe
        the feature you will add.</span></h3>
<p><span
        style="font-family: 'book antiqua', palatino, serif; font-size: 14pt;"><span
            style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">According to the Teams general post
            page, the Runestone interactive &ndash; author toolkit will need
            some features added to help make it easier for the authors of
            textbooks to maintain and make edits to their work. To begin, we
            will need to have the title of a few books to integrate into the
            dev container that is prebuilt for each authoring environment.
            These books will need to be prebuilt as well. And as a stretch
            goal, we will be looking for ways to easily make edits to the work
            by some type of &ldquo;edit&rdquo; or &ldquo;modify&rdquo;
            button.</span></span></p>
<h3><span
        style="font-family: 'book antiqua', palatino, serif; font-size: 14pt;"><span
            style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><span
                style="color: rgb(132, 63, 161);">Defines which
                repository/repositories your code will be added to.</span>
        </span></span></h3>
<p><span
        style="font-family: 'book antiqua', palatino, serif; font-size: 14pt;"><span
            style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">The Runestone-codespace repository is
            forked from <span style="color: rgb(52, 73, 94);"><a
                    style="color: rgb(52, 73, 94);"
                    href="https://github.com/bjones1/Runestone-codespace">https://github.com/bjones1/Runestone-codespace</a>
            </span>into both partners personal github account and then is
            cloned to a working copy on each remote machine. Smart Git is being
            utilized as the versioning and repository control software. The
            current plan is to take each party&rsquo;s work and commit to the
            forked branch and then independently make pull requests against
            that repo to the bjones1 repo upstream. </span></span></p>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3><span
        style="font-family: 'book antiqua', palatino, serif; font-size: 14pt; color: rgb(132, 63, 161);">Specify
        what libraries, languages, and interfaces your code must work
        with.&nbsp;</span></h3>
<p><span
        style="font-family: 'book antiqua', palatino, serif; font-size: 14pt;"><span
            style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Multiple languages and libraries are
            going to be required, starting with the docker-tools python3
            framework. Google Codespaces and dev containers will need to be
            understood to preconfigure environments that can be easily accessed
            by the VS Code IDE. Basic Linux command line interfaces and tools
            will be required as it is the operating system upon which the
            framework is built. Bash scripting, and HTML/JSON will also be
            required to work with the user interfaces. The Pretext language is
            a LaTex like language that is used for the authoring of books and
            will have to be reviewed and made familiar. To interface with the
            CLI for pretext, it may also be necessary to have a little TCL
            scripting ability. </span></span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
