<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3><span
        style="font-family: 'book antiqua', palatino, serif; font-size: 14pt; color: rgb(132, 63, 161);">Define
        tests to show the feature works correctly.</span></h3>
<p><span
        style="font-family: 'book antiqua', palatino, serif; font-size: 14pt;"><span
            style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">A unit test will be built alongside
            the development effort for each widget, button, or software feature
            added; and from the developers understanding of what the feature is
            supposed to do, we will create various what-if scenarios to
            validate the acceptable data inputs and the correct processing of
            valid data, but also guarding against input which violates the
            intent and logic functions performed by the code. It may even be
            necessary for one developer to write the test, while the other
            developer writes the code, so that timeline and schedule is not
            compromised. The Test-Driven-Development (TDD) mentality will be
            used to perform the project tasks.&nbsp;</span></span></p>
<h3><span
        style="color: rgb(132, 63, 161); font-size: 14pt; font-family: 'book antiqua', palatino, serif;">Outline
        goals for the draft pull request and final pull request.&nbsp;</span>
</h3>
<p><span
        style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-size: 14pt; font-family: 'book antiqua', palatino, serif;">For
        the initial draft pull request, the expectation is to have at least the
        environment ready for experimentation with at least one published book
        to be able to make rapid edits and changes to republish. The goal of
        the final pull request will be to incorporate instructor feedback and
        perform any feature cleanup. In addition to the delivery of a
        publishable, editable book for authors to use in a dev-container, it
        would also be good to have a suite of corresponding tests that can be
        run to ensure that the code is functioning as expected. The goal of our
        Sprint is to ensure that whatever is finally included in the last pull
        request is usable and deliverable. We will use our SCRUM meetings to
        make any decisions to strike features that are at risk of not being
        completed in time. Documentation of the Sprint Backlog will be
        maintained for any future teams to use in follow-up development
        efforts.</span></p>
